Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Line a #baking sheet{} with foil and brush with @vegetable oil{} or coat with @nonstick spray{}. Wash and dry all produce.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @red onion{1}; mince a few slices until you have 1 TBSP.

> For 4 servings: Mince a few slices of onion until you have 2 TBSP.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add sliced onion; cook for
~{3%minutes}. Stir in @ground pork{10%ounce} and @Southwest spice blend{1%tablespoon}; cook,
breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and onion is softened, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir in @Tex-Mex paste{1} and 1/3 cup water. Simmer until mixture is thickened and pork is
cooked through, ~{2-4%minutes} more. Turn off heat.

> For 4 servings: Stir in ½ cup water.

Meanwhile, drizzle @flour tortillas{6} with 1 TBSP @olive oil{1%tablespoon}; brush or rub to
completely coat.

Place tortillas on a clean work surface. Once pork filling is done, add a heaping ¼ cup
filling to one side of each tortilla, then sprinkle with 1 TBSP @Mexican cheese blend{½%cup}.
Roll up tortillas, starting with filled side, to create flautas. Place seam sides down on
prepared baking sheet.

Bake on middle rack until golden brown and crispy, ~{8-12%minutes}.

> For 4 servings: Drizzle tortillas with 2 TBSP olive oil.

> TIP: Make sure the flautas are snug on the sheet—this will prevent them from unrolling.

While flautas bake, finely dice @Roma tomato{1}. Zest and quarter @lime{1}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine tomato, minced onion, half the lime zest, and a squeeze of
lime juice. Season with @salt{}.

In a separate small bowl, combine @sour cream{4%tablespoon}, remaining lime zest, and a
squeeze of lime juice. Add water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling
consistency. Season with salt.

Divide flautas between plates. Top with pico de gallo, lime crema, and @guacamole{4%tablespoon}.
Serve.